				=09
					<div id=3D"mw-content-text" class=3D"mw-body-content"><div class=3D"mw=
-content-ltr mw-parser-output" lang=3D"en" dir=3D"ltr"><div class=3D"shortd=
escription nomobile noexcerpt noprint searchaux" style=3D"display:none">Exp=
eriment methodology</div>
<p class=3D"mw-empty-elt">
</p>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:A-B_testing_example.png" class=3D"mw-file-des=
cription"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/=
2/2e/A-B_testing_example.png/500px-A-B_testing_example.png" decoding=3D"asy=
nc" width=3D"350" height=3D"207" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=
=3D"919" data-file-height=3D"544"></a><figcaption>Example of A/B testing on=
 a website. Some users (chosen at random) are served a version of the websi=
te with a blue button, while others see a version with a green button. From=
 this, the relative efficacy of the two designs can be measured.</figcaptio=
n></figure>
<p><b>A/B testing</b> (also known as <b>bucket testing</b>, <b>split-run te=
sting</b> or <b>split testing</b>) is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/User_experience" title=3D"User experience">user-experience</a> resear=
ch method.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Young2014_1-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/A/B_testing#cite_note-Young2014-1"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
> A/B tests consist of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Randomize=
d_experiment" title=3D"Randomized experiment">randomized experiment</a> tha=
t usually involves two variants (A and B),<sup id=3D"cite_ref-2" class=3D"r=
eference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/A/B_testing#cite_note-2"=
><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span=
></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/A/B_testing#cite_note-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[=
</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
:1_4-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/A/B_te=
sting#cite_note-:1-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> although the concept can be also extended =
to multiple variants of the same variable. It includes application of <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistical_hypothesis_testing" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Statistical hypothesis testing">statistical hypot=
hesis testing</a> or "<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Two-sample_h=
ypothesis_testing" title=3D"Two-sample hypothesis testing">two-sample hypot=
hesis testing</a>" as used in the field of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Statistics" title=3D"Statistics">statistics</a>. A/B testing is em=
ployed to compare multiple versions of a single <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Variable_(mathematics)" title=3D"Variable (mathematics)">vari=
able</a>, for example by testing a subject's response to variant A against =
variant B, and to determine which of the variants is more effective.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-:0_5-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/A/B_testing#cite_note-:0-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Multivariate testing or multinomial testing is similar to A/B testin=
g but may test more than two versions at the same time or use more controls=
. Simple A/B tests are not valid for <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Observational" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Observational">observation=
al</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quasi-experimental" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Quasi-experimental">quasi-experimental</a> or oth=
er <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Non-experimental" class=3D"mw-r=
edirect" title=3D"Non-experimental">non-experimental</a> situations=E2=80=
=94commonplace with survey data, offline data, and other, more complex phen=
omena.
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Definition">Definition</h2>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DA/B_testing&amp;=
action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: Definition"><span>edi=
t</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>"A/B testing" is a shorthand for a simple randomized <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Controlling_for_a_variable" title=3D"Controlling for =
a variable">controlled</a> experiment, in which a number of samples (e.g. A=
 and B) of a single <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multivariate_r=
andom_variable" title=3D"Multivariate random variable">vector-variable</a> =
are compared.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Young2014_1-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/A/B_testing#cite_note-Young2014-1"><span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup> A/B tests are widely considered the simplest form of controlled experi=
ment, especially when they only involve two variants. However, by adding mo=
re variants to the test, its complexity grows.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:12_6-0" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/A/B_testing#ci=
te_note-:12-6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">]</span></a></sup>=20
</p><p>The following example illustrates an A/B test with a single variable=
:
</p><p>A company has a customer <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Da=
tabase" title=3D"Database">database</a> of 2,000 people and launches an ema=
il campaign with a discount code in order to generate sales through its web=
site. The company creates two versions of the email with different <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Call_to_action_(marketing)" title=3D"Call=
 to action (marketing)">calls to action</a> (the part of the copy that enco=
urages customers to act=E2=80=94in the case of a sales campaign, make a pur=
chase) and identifying promotional codes.
</p>
<ul><li>To 1,000 people, the company sends an email with the call to action=
 stating "Offer ends this Saturday! Use code A1",</li>
<li>To the remaining 1,000 people, it sends an email with the call to actio=
n stating "Offer ends soon! Use code B1".</li>
<li>All other elements of the emails' copy and layout are identical.</li></=
ul>
<p>The company then monitors which campaign has the higher success rate by =
analyzing the use of the promotional codes. The email using the code A1 has=
 a 5% <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Response_rate_(survey)" titl=
e=3D"Response rate (survey)">response rate</a> (50 of the 1,000 people emai=
led used the code to buy a product), and the email using the code B1 has a =
3% response rate (30 of the recipients used the code to buy a product). The=
 company therefore determines that in this instance, the first call to acti=
on is more effective and will use it in future sales. A more nuanced approa=
ch would involve applying statistical testing to determine whether the diff=
erences in response rates between A1 and B1 were <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Statistically_significant" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"St=
atistically significant">statistically significant</a> (highly likely that =
the differences are real, repeatable and the result to random chance).<sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-7" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/A/B_testing#cite_note-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In the previous example, the purpose of the test is to determine the=
 more effective strategy to encourage customers to make a purchase. If, how=
ever, the aim of the test had been to determine which email would generate =
the higher <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Clickthrough_rate" clas=
s=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Clickthrough rate">clickthrough rate</a> (the pe=
rcentage of people who actually click the link after receiving the email), =
the results might have been different.
</p><p>For example, even though more of the customers receiving the code B1=
 accessed the website, because the call to action did not state the end dat=
e of the promotion, many recipients may feel no urgency to make an immediat=
e purchase. Consequently, if the purpose of the test had been simply to det=
ermine which email would bring more traffic to the website, the email conta=
ining code B1 might well have been more successful. An A/B test should have=
 a defined, measurable outcome, such as sales converted, clickthrough rate =
or registration rate.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-8" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/A/B_testing#cite_note-8"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Common_test_statistics">Com=
mon test statistics</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-ed=
itsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?=
title=3DA/B_testing&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" title=3D"Edit sectio=
n: Common test statistics"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsecti=
on-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Two-sample_hypothesis_testing" =
title=3D"Two-sample hypothesis testing">Two-sample hypothesis tests</a> are=
 appropriate for comparing the two samples in which the samples are divided=
 by the two control cases in the experiment. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Z-test" title=3D"Z-test">Z-tests</a> are appropriate for compari=
ng means under stringent conditions regarding normality and a known standar=
d deviation. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Student%27s_t-test" t=
itle=3D"Student's t-test">Student's <i>t</i>-tests</a> are appropriate for =
comparing means under relaxed conditions when less is assumed. <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Welch%27s_t_test" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Welch's t test">Welch's <i>t</i>-test</a> assumes the least and is ther=
efore the most commonly used two-sample <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Hypothesis_test" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Hypothesis test">hypo=
thesis test</a> in which the mean of a metric is to be optimized. While the=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mean" title=3D"Mean">mean</a> of =
the variable to be optimized is the most common choice of <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Estimator" title=3D"Estimator">estimator</a>, other=
s are regularly used.
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fisher%27s_exact_test" titl=
e=3D"Fisher's exact test">Fisher's exact test</a> can be employed to compar=
e two <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binomial_distribution" title=
=3D"Binomial distribution">binomial distributions</a>, such as a <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Click-through_rate" title=3D"Click-through r=
ate">click-through rate</a>.
</p>
