<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Segmentation_and_targeting"=
>Segmentation and targeting</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/i=
ndex.php?title=3DA/B_testing&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D3" title=3D"Ed=
it section: Segmentation and targeting"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D=
"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>A/B tests most commonly apply the same variant (e.g., user interface ele=
ment) with equal probability to all users. However, in some circumstances, =
responses to variants may be heterogeneous. While a variant A might have a =
higher response rate overall, variant B may have an even higher response ra=
te within a specific segment of the customer base.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-10" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/A/B_testing#cit=
e_note-10"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>For instance, in the above example, the breakdown of the response ra=
tes by gender could have been:
</p>
<table class=3D"wikitable" style=3D"text-align:right">

<tbody><tr>
